# SecReEvalBench (reproduction / refactor)

This is a clean, modernized Python implementation of the evaluation workflow described in your paper draft.

It supports:

- 6 questioning sequences: **one-off**, **successive**, **successive-reverse**, **alternative**, **sequential-ascending**, **sequential-descending**.
- 4 metrics: **PARS**, **PARLS**, **CARS**, **CARTS**.
- Pluggable generation backends:
  - **Ollama** (recommended for quick local runs)
  - **Transformers** (HuggingFace, optional)
- Pluggable judges:
  - **Llama-Guard 3** (safety / maliciousness scoring; can be run via Ollama or Transformers)
  - **distilroberta-base-rejection-v1** (refusal detection; Transformers)
- A tunable conversation history policy for context-preserved sequences:
  - keep **full history** (paper default)
  - or keep only the **most recent N turns** (your requested feature)

Dataset support:

- Legacy: `SecEvalDatabase.JSON`
- Level-annotated: `SecEvalDatabase-with_levels.JSON` where each prompt includes `"level": "1"|"2"|"3"|"4"`.
  We map levels to prompt maliciousness **Ms** as:
  - level 1 → 1.00
  - level 2 → 0.66
  - level 3 → 0.33
  - level 4 → 0.00 (benign)

> ⚠️ Responsible use: this project sends the benchmark prompts (some are intentionally adversarial) to LLMs.
> Use only in controlled evaluation settings.

## Quickstart

### 1) Install

```bash
cd secreevalbench
python -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate  # Windows: .venv\Scripts\activate

# minimal install (Ollama backend)
pip install -e .

# OR, if you want HuggingFace Transformers backends/judges
pip install -e ".[transformers]"
```

### 2) Run (Ollama backend example)

Make sure Ollama is running and you have pulled the models you want to test.

```bash
# example: evaluate Qwen (generation) + Llama-Guard3 (judge) on successive sequence
secreeval run \
  --dataset ./data/SecEvalDatabase-with_levels.JSON \
  --provider ollama \
  --model qwen3:8b \
  --judge-provider ollama \
  --judge-guard-model llama-guard3:1b \
  --sequence successive \
  --history-window 4 \
  --out ./runs/qwen_successive_w4
```

### 3) Summarize

```bash
secreeval summarize --run-dir ./runs/qwen_successive_w4
```

## CLI reference (most useful switches)

- `--sequence {one_off,successive,successive_reverse,alternative,sequential_ascending,sequential_descending}`
- `--history-window N`:
  - `-1` = keep full chat history (paper default)
  - `0`  = no history (equivalent to always reset)
  - `N>0` = keep last **N turns** (a “turn” = user+assistant pair)
- `--store-text {true|false}`: whether to persist raw prompts/responses in output files

Outputs are written into `--out`:

- `turns.jsonl`: per-turn prompt/response + scores
- `summary.json`: metric aggregates
- `summary.csv`: a single-row CSV of the metrics
